course, could
have included Russia.

09:12.051 --> 09:13.987 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
STEVE INSKEEP: Countries
threatening their
neighbors.

09:14.020 --> 09:18.992 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
EVELYN FARKAS: Country
threatening using unorthodox
means, like cyber-attacks,
cyber-operations,

09:19.025 --> 09:22.162 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
strategic communications, fake
news, et cetera.

09:22.195 --> 09:26.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it also could have included
and probably
does include North Korea, as
well as China

09:26.199 --> 09:32.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and other actors, so other
actors that decide
to emulate, to copy Russia.

09:32.505 --> 09:36.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Russia is the biggest one,
because they're
really trying to rewrite the
rules of the

09:36.109 --> 09:40.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
international order far more
than China, although
China is pushing the envelope as
well.

09:40.079 --> 09:43.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: I want the bring
Ambassador
McFaul into the conversation,
but first let's

09:43.917 --> 09:47.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hear a contrary view here, what
sounds like
a contrary view.

09:47.487 --> 09:50.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know that the president-elect
seems to
want Russia as a friend.

09:50.757 --> 09:56.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Obama arguably has not
wanted to
say that Russia is that great of
a threat.

09:56.529 --> 09:58.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He doesn't seem all that worried
about them.

09:58.331 --> 10:00.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And let's listen a little bit of
the president
in December.

10:01.000 --> 10:07.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
The Russians can't change us or
significantly

10:07.574 --> 10:09.976 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
weaken us.

10:10.009 --> 10:11.277 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They are a smaller country.

10:11.311 --> 10:13.112 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They are a weaker country.

10:13.146 --> 10:17.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Their economy doesn't produce
anything that
anybody wants to buy, except oil
and gas and

10:17.917 --> 10:21.621 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
arms.

10:21.654 --> 10:26.793 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They don't innovate.

10:26.826 --> 10:32.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But they can impact us if we
lose track of
who we are.

10:33.032 --> 10:35.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: Ambassador
McFaul, that's your
former boss.

10:35.668 --> 10:37.403 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is Russia really that dangerous?

10:37.437 --> 10:40.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL, Former U.S.
Ambassador to
Russia: Well, I think Russia is
dangerous,

10:40.039 --> 10:41.107 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
not a superpower.

10:41.140 --> 10:42.976 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I know what the president is
trying to say.

10:43.009 --> 10:46.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I worked for him for five years,
not just
two.

10:46.446 --> 10:48.648 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He doesn't want us to overreact.

10:48.681 --> 10:52.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He doesn't want to go back to
the Cold War
and some superpower competition.

10:52.819 --> 10:57.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But my own view, and I think
General Mattis
stated something similar today,
is that Russia

10:57.390 --> 10:59.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is a challenge for the United
States.

10:59.259 --> 11:02.962 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is a threat to some of our
allies.

11:02.996 --> 11:07.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what means they have,
they're prepared
to use them.

11:07.100 --> 11:08.835 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's the big difference.

11:08.868 --> 11:11.037 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Take cyber-capabilities.

11:11.070 --> 11:13.773 align:left position:25%,start line:80% size:75%
We have way more
cyber-capability than they
do.

11:13.806 --> 11:17.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We could intervene in their
elections easily.

11:17.377 --> 11:20.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We choose not to do so because
we're a different
country.

11:20.280 --> 11:22.115 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's what Obama was trying to
say.

11:22.148 --> 11:25.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The means that Mr. Putin has,
he's not afraid
to use them.

11:25.952 --> 11:30.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: I'm remembering
the word asymmetric,
which we all had to learn after
9/11, when

11:30.823 --> 11:36.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we heard about asymmetric
threats, that al-Qaida
wasn't that large, not
conventionally powerful,

11:36.095 --> 11:40.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
didn't control territory, but
they found new
ways to project power that were
extraordinarily

11:40.533 --> 11:42.268 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
dangerous.

11:42.302 --> 11:46.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is this an asymmetric situation
with Russia,
where they are a relatively weak
country in

11:46.506 --> 11:49.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
many ways, but they have found
new ways to
strike out at their neighbors
and at the United

11:50.009 --> 11:51.311 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
States?

11:51.344 --> 11:55.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: I believe so, I
think in a
couple of instances.

11:55.448 --> 11:57.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Number one, I just mentioned
cyber.

11:57.517 --> 11:59.619 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have kinds of capabilities.

11:59.652 --> 12:04.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They use those capabilities in
different ways,
political ways, than we're
prepared to do

12:04.824 --> 12:06.526 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
so.

12:06.559 --> 12:09.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With respect to their military,
of course
they don't have the military
means at all

12:09.896 --> 12:12.532 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
compared to the United States of
America.

12:12.565 --> 12:17.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they were prepared to use
their military
to annex territory on their
neighbor and then

12:17.737 --> 12:19.872 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
intervene in Eastern Ukraine.

12:19.906 --> 12:21.908 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're not prepared to do that.

12:21.941 --> 12:28.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, number three, I think
something
that's really understudied and
misunderstood

12:28.081 --> 12:31.651 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is their use of information.

12:31.684 --> 12:37.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are very bold in the world
of information,
propagating their ideas, using
companies like

12:37.323 --> 12:39.492 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
R.T. and Sputnik to do that.

12:39.525 --> 12:42.261 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, again, they don't play by
the same rules.

12:42.295 --> 12:49.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we call news, fact vs.
fiction, they're
a lot more loose in terms of
those definitions.

12:49.135 --> 12:53.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that has a greater effect,
therefore,
because they play by different
rules.

12:53.039 --> 12:57.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: Evelyn Farkas,
the Republican
critique here is that Russia is
in a weak

12:58.011 --> 13:02.649 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
situation, but has been
emboldened by a weak
response from the United States,
that in Ukraine,

13:02.682 --> 13:05.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that in other places, the United
States has
not stepped forward.

13:05.351 --> 13:07.053 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is there some justice in that
view?

13:07.086 --> 13:13.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVELYN FARKAS: I regretfully say
there is
some justice in the view,
because the only

13:13.359 --> 13:18.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
thing that the Kremlin, this
cadre of people
supporting Vladimir Putin, and
Vladimir Putin

13:18.398 --> 13:22.001 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
himself understand is strength,
is resolve.

13:22.035 --> 13:27.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they will not stop until
they are given
the sense that the costs will be
too high

13:27.340 --> 13:29.042 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and they will have gone too far.

13:29.075 --> 13:35.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other part of this is that
Putin himself
is a bit of a risk taker, so the
invading

13:35.381 --> 13:40.820 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Ukraine, in the east in
particular -- Crimea
was risky, but then the east was
risky.

13:40.853 --> 13:43.423 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And actually then he didn't pull
it off completely.

13:43.456 --> 13:45.591 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And then Syria was very risky.

13:45.625 --> 13:49.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Both these operations, as Mike
pointed out,
were using their military, but
they actually

13:49.495 --> 13:51.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
didn't use their whole military
either.

13:51.864 --> 13:53.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They were pretty much economies
of force.

13:53.766 --> 13:56.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think, yes, of course we
need to be
stronger.

13:56.335 --> 13:58.304 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We need to deter the Russians.

13:58.337 --> 14:02.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need to show resolve, which
is why cooperating
with them on the other hand can
be more difficult.

14:02.475 --> 14:06.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: Well, let's talk
explicitly
about Russian President Vladimir
Putin and

14:06.813 --> 14:08.314 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
president-elect Trump.

14:08.347 --> 14:11.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President-elect Trump talked
about Putin at
his news conference yesterday.

14:11.250 --> 14:13.086 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Let's listen to a little bit of
that.

14:13.119 --> 14:17.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DONALD TRUMP (R),
President-Elect: If Putin
likes Donald Trump, I consider
that an asset,

14:17.457 --> 14:21.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not a liability, because we have
a horrible
relationship with Russia.

14:21.094 --> 14:24.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russia can help us fight ISIS,
which, by the
way, is, number one, tricky.

14:24.797 --> 14:28.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: And I want to add
one other
thing, Ambassador McFaul,
because Donald Trump

14:28.701 --> 14:30.336 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
sent out a tweet the other day.

14:30.369 --> 14:32.071 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm sure you noticed it.

14:32.105 --> 14:36.776 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He said: "Having a good
relationship with
Russia is a good thing, not a
bad thing.

14:36.809 --> 14:41.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Only stupid people or fools
would think it
was bad."

14:41.414 --> 14:42.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: Felt that was
directed at
me.

14:42.515 --> 14:43.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: You think it was
directed at
you?

14:43.750 --> 14:44.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's wrong with having a good
relationship
with Russia?

14:44.617 --> 14:46.986 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: Well, first, two
things.

14:47.019 --> 14:52.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I want to be clear that when you
mention the
Republican critique of President
Obama, that

14:52.291 --> 14:55.161 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is not president-elect Trump's
critique, right?

14:55.194 --> 15:00.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So you have a real clash within
the Republican
Party, and I think within the
Trump administration,

15:00.767 --> 15:03.269 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about how to develop policy
toward Russia.

15:03.302 --> 15:08.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But here's what I would say to
that tweet:
It should never be the goal of
U.S. foreign

15:08.608 --> 15:13.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
policy towards any country to
have a -- quote,
unquote -- "good relation."

15:13.279 --> 15:14.313 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Then what?

15:14.347 --> 15:16.249 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do we get out of that?

15:16.282 --> 15:20.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We get -- Trump is helping the
approval ratings
amongst Russians.

15:20.086 --> 15:23.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How does that advance American
national security
interests?

15:23.289 --> 15:25.158 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think you have got to flip it
around.

15:25.191 --> 15:31.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has got to define what he
seeks to achieve
with Russia, and then use
diplomacy and sometimes

15:31.430 --> 15:33.599 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
coercion to achieve those ends.

15:33.633 --> 15:38.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Right now, aside from this fight
with ISIS,
which I would just underscore,
you know, the

15:38.805 --> 15:43.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obama administration has been
trying to fight
ISIS with Russia for several
years now.

15:43.943 --> 15:45.745 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's no disagreement there.

15:45.778 --> 15:49.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They just have not been useful,
because the
Russians don't want the fight
ISIS in Syria.

15:49.282 --> 15:51.217 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They want to leave that to us.

15:51.250 --> 15:55.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Aside from that, I don't know
what are the
objectives that Mr. Trump seeks
in having

15:56.022 --> 15:57.757 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a good relationship with Mr.
Putin.

15:57.790 --> 16:01.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: Well, that leads
to one more
point, Evelyn Farkas, because in
the Senate

16:01.494 --> 16:06.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hearing today, Senator John
McCain said Russia
is not going to be our friend.

16:06.332 --> 16:09.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In fact, he said Russia wants
and needs to
be our enemy.

16:09.101 --> 16:10.436 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EVELYN FARKAS: Right.

16:10.469 --> 16:12.138 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: And they're not
going to cooperate
even on ISIS.

16:12.171 --> 16:14.440 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, what can the United States
achieve, then?

16:14.473 --> 16:18.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVELYN FARKAS: I mean, we can
try to get them
to cooperate on ISIS, but, as
Mike pointed

16:18.411 --> 16:22.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out, we spent months in the
administration
trying to get them to cooperate
on terrorism,

16:22.315 --> 16:25.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actually starting with the Sochi
Olympics,
where it was on their territory.

16:25.318 --> 16:27.486 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You would have thought they
would have wanted
to cooperate.

16:27.520 --> 16:31.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think you pointed to a
very important
point we need to bear in mind,
which is the

16:31.524 --> 16:33.526 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Russian domestic situation.

16:33.559 --> 16:41.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 2018, Vladimir Putin will be
up for reelection,
and he has shifted his whole
political strategy

16:41.067 --> 16:45.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
inside of Russia from one where
he promised
the Russians pretty much a
chicken in every

16:45.271 --> 16:47.807 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pot, a better economic way of
life.

16:47.840 --> 16:49.675 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He's now nationalist.

16:49.709 --> 16:53.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what he does is, he tells
the Russian
people, OK, you may have a
little less chicken

16:53.179 --> 16:56.616 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in your pot, but I'm making
Russia great again.

16:56.649 --> 16:58.017 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Look what we're doing all other
the world.

16:58.050 --> 16:59.952 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Everyone is paying attention to
us.

16:59.986 --> 17:03.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Russia is a great power, on
par with the
United States and others.

17:03.923 --> 17:08.194 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And he -- and the
anti-Americanism is rampant
in Russia right now.

17:08.227 --> 17:09.996 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He can tone it back.

17:10.029 --> 17:12.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's going to have to tone it
back if he wants
a good relationship with Donald
Trump, but

17:12.698 --> 17:16.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he's going to have to probably
shift back
to that again, because the
Russian people

17:16.502 --> 17:20.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are not going to be interested
in having a
guy give them a raw economic
deal for another

17:20.539 --> 17:22.241 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
term.

17:22.275 --> 17:24.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: Ambassador
McFaul, is there
just one thing you can name that
the United

17:24.477 --> 17:26.112 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
States could deal with Russia
on?

17:26.145 --> 17:29.382 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: Well, of course
we can deal
with them on counterterrorism.

17:29.415 --> 17:31.183 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have and I think we are right
now.

17:31.217 --> 17:32.718 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's easy.

17:32.752 --> 17:38.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think in other economic and
trade issues,
under the right conditions.

17:38.424 --> 17:41.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, again, I guess I want to
really emphasize
this point.

17:41.894 --> 17:46.198 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Vladimir Putin knows exactly
what he wants
from this relationship.

17:46.232 --> 17:52.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In return for good relations, he
wants lifting
of sanctions, ratification,
approval of his

17:52.071 --> 17:57.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wars in Ukraine and Syria, and
his dream of
dreams, an acknowledgment of his
sphere of

17:57.243 --> 18:00.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
influence in Ukraine and the
former Soviet
Union.

18:00.212 --> 18:03.082 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That, to me, is a bad deal.

18:03.115 --> 18:06.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once he understands that we're
not going to
take that deal, then we can move
on to these

18:06.619 --> 18:10.790 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
other things, but, first and
foremost, he
wants to test that proposition.

18:10.823 --> 18:15.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he's waiting to see what
President Trump
will do when given that deal on
offer.

18:15.895 --> 18:18.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: Michael McFaul is
a former
U.S. ambassador to Russia.

18:19.031 --> 18:22.935 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Evelyn Farkas is a former
Pentagon official
here in our studios.

18:22.969 --> 18:26.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thanks to you both.

18:26.706 --> 18:32.244 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
EVELYN FARKAS: Thank you very
much.

18:32.278 --> 18:38.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Moving away from
Russia, Mr.
Trump's picks to lead the CIA
and Department

18:38.084 --> 18:43.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Defense shed light on where
the new administration
stands on a number of other
fronts.

