JUDY WOODRUFF: The president is
leaving office
with a high approval rating,
over 50 percent.

27:39.157 --> 27:41.393 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's getting credit from many
quarters.

27:41.426 --> 27:46.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there is also criticism out
there, including
from Democrats, that he didn't
do enough to

27:46.398 --> 27:50.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reach out to members of Congress
to get his
agenda accomplished, that he
should have done

27:50.269 --> 27:53.272 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
more, gone the extra mile.

27:53.305 --> 27:55.073 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is that a fair criticism?

27:55.107 --> 27:58.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: Well, you know,
Judy, I have
been here since day one, January
20 of 2009.

27:58.377 --> 28:01.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have watched how hard the
president
has worked.

28:01.146 --> 28:05.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have watched how every single
day, he comes
to the office focused on one
thing, and that's

28:05.951 --> 28:08.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what's in the best interest of
the American
people.

28:08.186 --> 28:09.721 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He has rolled up his sleeves.

28:09.755 --> 28:12.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's worked as hard as I have
ever seen a
president work.

28:12.658 --> 28:15.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that includes his outreach
the members
of Congress.

28:15.360 --> 28:16.995 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, should we have done more?

28:17.029 --> 28:19.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, of course, you always wish
you could
do more.

28:19.398 --> 28:20.999 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The work is never finished.

28:21.033 --> 28:22.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I think he's proud of his
record.

28:22.901 --> 28:29.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You have been at
moments critical
of Republicans for not attending
state dinners,

28:29.374 --> 28:34.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for not participating in some of
the events
that they were invited to by
this White House,

28:34.980 --> 28:38.083 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for not engaging more in the
other direction.

28:38.116 --> 28:41.086 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Right now, the Democrats are on
the outs.

28:41.119 --> 28:42.287 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Should they engage?

28:42.321 --> 28:44.356 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: Well, I think
they will.

28:44.389 --> 28:49.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, I think part of what we
have learned
certainly over the course of the
last eight

28:49.494 --> 28:54.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
years is, if the Republicans had
engaged,
even though we're very proud of
the progress

28:54.633 --> 28:56.735 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have made, we would be so
much further.

28:56.768 --> 29:00.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what I observed in my
criticism really,
Judy, was much deeper than
whether or not

29:00.739 --> 29:04.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they attend a state dinner,
although I can't
imagine why anyone wouldn't want
to come and

29:04.109 --> 29:07.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
represent our country when we
are inviting
foreign dignitaries here.

29:07.879 --> 29:13.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the real point is, they put
their short-term
political interests ahead of
what was best

29:13.452 --> 29:15.253 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for our country.

29:15.287 --> 29:18.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Vice President
Biden said the
other day, when I spoke with
him, he said:

29:18.724 --> 29:25.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We were not clear enough in this
election
that we understood the pressure
working people,

29:25.097 --> 29:29.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
working Americans were under,
and that we
had concrete solutions to that.

29:29.768 --> 29:31.937 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We never got that across to
them.

29:31.970 --> 29:35.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: Yes, we had a
hard time getting
that message out.

29:35.607 --> 29:39.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there was -- it's troubling,
Judy, because
there was a disconnect between
the policies

29:39.444 --> 29:47.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the president has embraced
since he was
first campaigning back in 2007
and '8, and

29:47.185 --> 29:51.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the feeling that many people
have that those
policies were not meant for
them.

29:51.723 --> 29:53.525 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But they certainly were.

29:53.558 --> 29:57.629 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The president has always
believed in growing
the middle class, providing room
for everybody.

29:57.663 --> 29:59.965 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so it's certainly what the
president believes.

29:59.998 --> 30:04.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think what the vice
president said and
what the president believes is,
is that the

30:04.169 --> 30:06.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Democratic Party has to do a
better job of
reaching out.

30:06.071 --> 30:10.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Donald Trump has
tweeted a
few times in December about the
economy.

30:10.676 --> 30:14.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At one point, he wrote: "The
world was gloomy
before I won.

30:14.579 --> 30:15.547 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There was no hope.

30:15.580 --> 30:18.083 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now the market is up nearly 10
percent.

30:18.116 --> 30:20.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Christmas spending is over $1
trillion."

30:20.485 --> 30:23.155 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In another tweet, he took credit
for rising
consumer confidence.

30:23.188 --> 30:28.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: I think that,
if you look
at what has happened over the
last eight years,

30:28.660 --> 30:33.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in large part due to the grit
and determination
of the American people, we have
rebuilt our

30:33.665 --> 30:35.367 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
economy, and it is strong.

30:35.400 --> 30:37.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we're real proud that we're
going to turn
it over in as good a shape as
it's in.

30:38.003 --> 30:41.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, no particular
reaction
to what he said?

30:41.073 --> 30:42.941 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He was wrong?

30:42.974 --> 30:48.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: Well, what
incoming president
who is enjoying a good economy
wouldn't want

30:48.847 --> 30:50.749 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to figure out how they can take
credit for
it?

30:50.782 --> 30:52.617 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think that's par for the
course.

30:52.651 --> 30:57.456 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: As new
information is coming
out about Russian interference
in the election,

30:57.489 --> 31:01.026 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in retrospect, should President
Obama have
called out the Russians earlier?

31:01.059 --> 31:03.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He had information earlier that
this was going
on.

31:03.695 --> 31:07.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: You know, he --
the one thing
I can say to you about the
president is that

31:07.999 --> 31:09.601 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
he is thoughtful.

31:09.634 --> 31:11.303 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He's deliberate.

31:11.336 --> 31:14.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He takes in all the information
he has, and
then he makes the best judgment
he can.

31:14.573 --> 31:17.509 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he's very comfortable with
the decision
he made.

31:17.542 --> 31:23.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Has his thinking
changed about
what he's going to do after
being president,

31:23.048 --> 31:25.317 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
after being in office, given the
result?

31:25.350 --> 31:28.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Does he feel more of a
responsibility now
to go out and defend his legacy?

31:28.286 --> 31:33.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: I think he will
speak out
when he thinks his voice can
move the needle,

31:33.492 --> 31:38.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
make a difference, and be an
inspiration to
those who are looking for
positive change

31:39.030 --> 31:39.998 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in our country.

31:40.031 --> 31:41.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what about
Valerie Jarrett?

31:41.867 --> 31:46.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I saw you quoted as saying you
were going
to be moving between your
hometown of Chicago,

31:46.438 --> 31:49.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Washington, where your daughter
is, and some
other places.

31:49.274 --> 31:50.242 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What about you?

31:50.275 --> 31:51.743 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: Lots of sleep.

31:51.777 --> 31:55.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, after I have had some
rest, I will
make some decisions.

31:55.046 --> 31:58.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you think you
will continue
to work with President Obama and
Mrs. Obama?

31:58.350 --> 32:02.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: Oh, I will help
President
Obama and Mrs. Obama for the
rest of my life

32:02.921 --> 32:04.089 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in any way that I can.

32:04.122 --> 32:06.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Run for public
office?

32:06.458 --> 32:07.893 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: You know what?

32:07.926 --> 32:10.595 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're not first person who has
asked me that
question.

32:10.629 --> 32:14.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I toyed with it, as you would
probably remember,
when the president was elected
and there was

32:14.933 --> 32:16.701 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a vacancy in his seat.

32:16.735 --> 32:20.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he appealed to me and said:
You know,
I know what it's like in the
Senate.

32:20.939 --> 32:23.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I know what I want to do
here in the White
House.

32:23.108 --> 32:24.876 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think you will be happier
here.

32:24.910 --> 32:25.877 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And, boy, was he right.

32:25.911 --> 32:26.878 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So, we will see.

32:26.912 --> 32:28.680 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But you're not
ruling it out?

32:28.713 --> 32:33.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALERIE JARRETT: I'm not ruling
out anything
right now, because I know, after
eight years

32:33.418 --> 32:41.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
here, you are not in a position
to make any
really important, long decisions
that affect

32:41.493 --> 32:42.460 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
your life.

32:42.494 --> 32:43.461 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I know that I need some rest.

32:43.495 --> 32:45.197 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I need to gain some perspective.

32:45.230 --> 32:49.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I still want to continue to work
on issues
that I care a great deal about,
and to be

32:49.501 --> 32:51.303 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as helpful as I can.

32:51.336 --> 32:56.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, whether that leads me to
elected office,
or whether it leads me to help a
not-for-profit

32:56.041 --> 32:58.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's trying to do something
important, we
will see.

32:58.343 --> 33:05.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Valerie Jarrett,
thank you
so much.

33:05.717 --> 33:19.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: We're going to
dig a little
deeper now into the economic
legacy of President

33:19.364 --> 33:21.132 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Obama.

33:21.166 --> 33:24.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He came into office at a
desperate moment,
amid a financial crisis and the
great recession.

33:24.836 --> 33:28.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's gotten some of the credit
for a long
and sustained recovery.

33:28.240 --> 33:32.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there are just as many
questions about
whether he took the right steps
and helped

33:32.244 --> 33:33.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the right people.

33:33.545 --> 33:36.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For many people, wages are only
now starting
to climb.

33:36.848 --> 33:40.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Economics correspondent Paul
Solman has the
story, part of his weekly series
on Thursdays,

33:40.986 --> 33:43.655 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Making Sense.

33:43.688 --> 33:49.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
And it is good to be back in
Chicago.

33:49.794 --> 33:51.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

33:51.229 --> 33:52.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: President Obama in
2010 at Ford's
Chicago assembly plant.

33:53.031 --> 33:58.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA: The year before I
took office,
this industry lost hundreds of
thousands of

33:58.536 --> 34:00.539 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
jobs.

34:00.572 --> 34:05.944 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sales plunged 40 percent -- 40
percent.

34:05.977 --> 34:11.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two of the big three automakers,
GM and Chrysler,
were on the brink of
liquidation.

34:11.383 --> 34:13.285 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

34:13.318 --> 34:19.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA: And I'm convinced
-- I'm convinced
we're going to rebuild not only
the auto industry,

34:19.958 --> 34:23.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but the economy better and
stronger than before.

34:23.161 --> 34:28.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And at its heart is going to be
three powerful
words: Made in America.

34:28.400 --> 34:29.367 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Made in America.

34:29.401 --> 34:31.202 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

34:31.236 --> 34:35.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And, indeed, say
local union
officials, nine years after the
crash of '08:

34:35.206 --> 34:38.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS PENA, Union President: We
have more
people working in our facility
than we ever

34:38.076 --> 34:39.411 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
have now.

34:39.444 --> 34:42.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we have also been working
24/7 on three
production shifts.

34:42.714 --> 34:46.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT HOULDIESON, UAW Local 551:
There wouldn't
be an auto industry that looks
like what we

34:46.318 --> 34:48.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have today had it not been for
the bailout.

34:48.887 --> 34:53.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Ever since Obama
then, the U.S.
auto industry has been going
gangbusters,

34:53.992 --> 34:55.794 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the stock market too.

34:55.827 --> 34:58.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDY WILLIAMS JR., Foreclosure
Activist: You
will see a lot of houses will be
boarded up.

34:58.096 --> 35:02.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But when it comes
to victims
of the housing collapse, says
foreclosure

35:02.500 --> 35:04.169 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
activist Andy Williams Jr.:

35:04.202 --> 35:05.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANDY WILLIAMS JR.: Look at our
conditions
in our neighborhood.

35:05.603 --> 35:06.571 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's still terrible.

35:06.604 --> 35:08.707 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It still needs to be
revitalized.

35:08.740 --> 35:13.878 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So what is the
economic legacy
of Barack Obama?

35:13.912 --> 35:17.582 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Robust recovery, or too little,
too late?

35:17.615 --> 35:23.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the shadow of Chicago's Trump
Tower, at
the annual convening of the
economics profession,

35:23.955 --> 35:27.425 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we assembled a panel to assess
the record.

35:27.459 --> 35:31.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Cecilia Rouse served on the
president's Council
of Economic Advisers from 2009
to 2011.

35:31.629 --> 35:35.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CECILIA ROUSE, Former Council of
Economic
Advisers Member: I think that
what President

35:35.166 --> 35:39.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obama did was, he rescued an
economy that
was in freefall.

35:39.037 --> 35:41.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that he saved us
from a great
depression.

35:42.007 --> 35:46.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obviously, we would love for
economic growth
to have been more robust in the
years since.

35:46.511 --> 35:48.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I think it has been a
success.

35:48.046 --> 35:50.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Alan Krueger also
served on the
Council.

35:50.515 --> 35:51.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER, Former Chairman,
White House
Council of Economic Advisers: We
have had

35:51.750 --> 35:53.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
75 straight months of job
growth.

35:53.618 --> 35:58.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Over 15 million jobs have been
added; 22 million
more people have health
insurance coverage

35:58.256 --> 36:00.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
than they did before.

36:00.091 --> 36:04.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's in spite of the fact that
many of the
tools that President Obama
requested to help

36:04.529 --> 36:09.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
strengthen the recovery, like
investing more
in infrastructure or raising the
minimum wage,

36:09.601 --> 36:11.569 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Congress refused to act on.

36:11.603 --> 36:16.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But from the left,
Darrick Hamilton,
president of the mostly
African-American National

36:16.341 --> 36:18.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Economic Association, begged to
differ.

36:18.676 --> 36:21.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DARRICK HAMILTON, President,
National Economic
Association: I would say it was
a missed opportunity.

36:22.013 --> 36:27.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He certainly faced a catastrophe
when he came
into office, but nothing
fundamentally changed

36:27.285 --> 36:29.220 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the trajectory towards
inequality.

36:29.254 --> 36:34.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we characterize an economy as
being in
a catastrophe at unemployment
rates greater

36:34.826 --> 36:38.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than 8 percent, the black
unemployment rate
is still above 8 percent.

36:39.030 --> 36:44.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, frankly, black Americans are
still in
a great depression, or great
recession at

36:44.869 --> 36:46.704 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the very least.

36:46.738 --> 36:50.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Glenn Hubbard, who
ran President
George W. Bush's economic
council, differed

36:50.942 --> 36:52.710 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
from the right.

36:52.744 --> 36:53.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GLENN HUBBARD, Former Chairman,
White House
Council of Economic Advisers: I
think there

36:53.611 --> 36:55.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
were two very big missed
opportunities.

36:55.246 --> 36:58.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The first was a failure by the
Obama administration
to focus on economic growth.

36:58.850 --> 37:03.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there's a second missed
opportunity that's
really bipartisan, and I think
Republicans

37:03.188 --> 37:06.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
share blame in as well, which is
the failure
to support work.

37:06.991 --> 37:10.228 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We need to support work by
low-skilled people.

37:10.261 --> 37:12.030 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's not a free lunch.

37:12.063 --> 37:16.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That is a dramatic expansion in
the Earned
Income Tax Credit, particularly
for childless

37:16.568 --> 37:20.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
workers, who would typically be
younger men
and women entering the labor
force.

37:20.672 --> 37:26.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Let's take these
alleged missed
opportunities in turn, starting
with continuing

37:26.111 --> 37:28.813 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
inequality, especially for
African-Americans.

37:28.847 --> 37:34.686 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CECILIA ROUSE: In fact,
President Obama has
put in more policies to try to
pull that back,

37:34.719 --> 37:37.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
through increased improvements
in the EITC,
through the Affordable Care Act.

37:38.022 --> 37:40.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: That's the Earned
Income Tax
Credit.

37:40.325 --> 37:43.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CECILIA ROUSE: The tax credit,
so that we
actually saw more progress on
reducing inequality

37:43.361 --> 37:46.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than had been made in -- since I
think the
Johnson administration.

37:46.798 --> 37:52.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER: Last year, we saw
the strongest
median income growth since the
Bureau of Labor

37:52.770 --> 37:54.806 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Statistics has been collecting
data.

37:54.839 --> 37:58.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We saw the biggest drop in
poverty since they
started collecting, since the
1960s.

37:58.943 --> 38:03.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
CECILIA ROUSE: Yes, the
African-American unemployment
rate is unacceptably high.

38:03.615 --> 38:05.817 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It came down from a high of 16.8
percent.

38:05.850 --> 38:07.819 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's down to 7.9 percent.

38:07.852 --> 38:09.354 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Do we need to do more?

38:09.387 --> 38:10.855 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Absolutely.

38:10.889 --> 38:12.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there has been progress, and
I think it's
important to recognize that.

38:12.891 --> 38:13.858 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
PAUL SOLMAN: No?

38:13.892 --> 38:15.660 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's not true?

38:15.693 --> 38:18.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DARRICK HAMILTON: Well, we
consider the types
of jobs and the fact that it is
still 7.9

38:18.229 --> 38:20.064 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
percent.

38:20.098 --> 38:23.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then if we invoke the
paramount indicator
of economic security, wealth,
then we know

38:23.801 --> 38:27.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there's virtually no progress
that's been
made under the Barack Obama
administration.

38:27.071 --> 38:29.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So I'm looking at
the numbers
here.

38:29.941 --> 38:38.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Since 2007, November of 2007,
jobs added by
race or ethnicity, Hispanic,
five million,

38:38.383 --> 38:44.589 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
almost, black,
two-point-something million,
Asians, same, white down by a
million jobs,

38:44.622 --> 38:46.391 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
just about.

38:46.424 --> 38:51.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, wouldn't you, if you were a
rural white
American, think this
administration simply

38:51.829 --> 38:53.431 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
didn't do anything for me?

38:53.464 --> 38:55.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DARRICK HAMILTON: That's a
delusion.

38:55.366 --> 39:00.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The notion that white Americans
are suffering,
well, they're facing greater
competition than

39:00.371 --> 39:01.906 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they have perhaps in the past.

39:01.940 --> 39:04.842 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It still doesn't fundamentally
change the
structure of where we are.

39:04.876 --> 39:13.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But hasn't white
America under
the Obama administration been
left behind,

39:13.885 --> 39:16.788 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or certainly feel that it's been
left behind?

39:16.821 --> 39:21.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER: Look, we lost over
eight million
jobs in 2008 and 2009.

39:21.993 --> 39:25.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That was a very big hole to dig
our way out
of.

39:25.563 --> 39:28.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The trend would've been much
worse if we'd
not -- had not started on the
recovery.

39:28.900 --> 39:33.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, the president proposed
in the American
Jobs Act additional
infrastructure spending,

39:34.005 --> 39:39.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
support for state and local
governments, which
Congress only enacted a small
part of.

39:39.410 --> 39:41.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Still, said the
critics from
the left and right:

39:41.980 --> 39:46.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GLENN HUBBARD: A long-term
infrastructure
program would have made a great
deal of sense,

39:46.384 --> 39:48.653 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and frankly still does today.

39:48.686 --> 39:50.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But that's not what the Obama
administration
proposed.

39:50.788 --> 39:56.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we need to have a more
holistic structural
agenda for lower-income
Americans, rather

39:56.761 --> 40:00.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than just treating it as a
problem of recession
and recovery.

40:00.164 --> 40:05.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The advice would be to focus on
skill development
and on support for work.

40:05.136 --> 40:07.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DARRICK HAMILTON: And Glenn --
Glenn actually
proposed Something.

40:07.872 --> 40:13.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said, had the original jobs
bill around
infrastructure had been targeted
to be more

40:13.478 --> 40:16.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
permanent, that that could've
fundamentally
changed the structure of the
economy.

40:17.015 --> 40:21.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CECILIA ROUSE: I want to just
jump in on the
skills development, because
there was increases

40:21.286 --> 40:24.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the Pell Grant to make them
more available
to more students.

40:24.722 --> 40:26.858 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There were investments in
student loans.

40:26.891 --> 40:28.226 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER: And record high
school graduation.

40:28.259 --> 40:30.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CECILIA ROUSE: And record high
school graduation
rates last year.

40:30.695 --> 40:33.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the administration was
focused on skills
development.

40:33.298 --> 40:36.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we would have liked to
have done more,
but, again, we were working with
a Congress

40:36.434 --> 40:37.802 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that wasn't so cooperative.

40:37.835 --> 40:39.704 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Isn't that fair?

40:39.737 --> 40:42.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GLENN HUBBARD: I think the Obama
administration
did make several efforts in
skill development.

40:42.507 --> 40:45.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I just don't think there was
enough of a structural
focus.

40:45.677 --> 40:51.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We just had a presidential
election that shook
the country, because I think the
view that

40:51.282 --> 40:56.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
many economic elites had on both
sides of
the aisle wasn't that connected
with the skills

40:56.387 --> 40:58.790 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and employment prospects of many
Americans.

40:58.823 --> 41:02.593 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, I think, while the
administration made
some progress, it clearly wasn't
enough.

41:02.627 --> 41:05.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER: Don't forget, it
wasn't the
president who was on the ballot.

41:05.596 --> 41:09.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the Democratic candidate did
receive three
million more votes.

41:09.267 --> 41:13.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think it's difficult to
interpret the
election as a reflection of the
president's

41:13.604 --> 41:15.673 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
economic agenda and his economic
results.

41:15.707 --> 41:16.874 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
PAUL SOLMAN: No?

41:16.908 --> 41:18.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GLENN HUBBARD: I disagree with
that.

41:18.376 --> 41:22.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Republicans control the
Congress and the
White House.

41:22.180 --> 41:26.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I don't think history will
be that kind
to the latter part of the
administration's

41:26.317 --> 41:27.418 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
legacy.

41:27.452 --> 41:28.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DARRICK HAMILTON: I mean, I
would agree with
Glenn.

41:28.619 --> 41:30.088 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I can't believe I keep saying
that.

41:30.121 --> 41:31.856 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

41:31.889 --> 41:34.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DARRICK HAMILTON: I would agree
with Glenn,
in that Obama's economic legacy
was on the

41:34.359 --> 41:35.960 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
table in this election.

41:35.993 --> 41:39.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump put it on the table, front
and center,
along with a lot of other
things.

41:39.464 --> 41:42.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think Obama actually
campaigned to defend
his economic legacy.

41:42.900 --> 41:48.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We needed bolder, stronger, more
fundamental,
not tinkering, ideas to really
structurally

41:48.906 --> 41:49.974 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
change the U.S. economy.

41:50.007 --> 41:51.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CECILIA ROUSE: Absolutely, the
bolder the
better.

41:52.009 --> 41:57.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, you know, the president is
not king,
and he can't just wave a magic
wand and do

41:57.248 --> 41:59.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
all that he wants to do.

41:59.083 --> 42:01.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Like help many of
the people
who lost their homes in the
financial crisis.

42:01.919 --> 42:03.855 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANDY WILLIAMS JR.: I think it
was backwards.

42:03.888 --> 42:07.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the money should have
been given to
the people to revitalize the
community, and

42:07.792 --> 42:11.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not help the ones who were part
of the problem
and not the solution.

42:11.295 --> 42:14.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Again, both the
left and right
had a similar prescription.

42:14.665 --> 42:16.801 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
GLENN HUBBARD: A mass
refinancing of home
mortgages.

42:16.834 --> 42:18.536 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DARRICK HAMILTON: As opposed to
thinking about
banks.

42:18.569 --> 42:22.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, I put the final
question
to one of the president's former
chief economic

42:22.507 --> 42:24.142 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
advisers.

42:24.175 --> 42:28.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER: Which is, wasn't
it unfair that
the banking system got
rescued...

42:28.913 --> 42:30.648 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Yes.

42:30.681 --> 42:33.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER: ... auto sector
got rescued,
and a lot of the rest of the
U.S. economy

42:33.251 --> 42:35.253 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was left to fend for its own?

42:35.286 --> 42:36.287 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Absolutely.

42:36.320 --> 42:38.189 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was fundamentally unfair.

42:38.222 --> 42:43.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was necessary, however,
because the consequences
would've been much worse for the
U.S. economy

42:43.294 --> 42:45.630 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if the financial sector was
allowed to implode.

42:45.663 --> 42:47.432 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, certainly, there's much
more to be done.

42:47.465 --> 42:51.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And it will be up
to a new administration
to do it.

42:51.335 --> 42:57.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Reporting from Chicago, this is
economics
correspondent Paul Solman.

42:57.241 --> 43:11.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: a profile of
an artist
who has lived on three
continents and explores

43:11.389 --> 43:14.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
history and identity in today's
global culture.

43:14.792 --> 43:16.694 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has our story.

43:16.727 --> 43:22.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: On a recent
morning in Washington,
D.C., this wind sculpture was
lifted in and

43:22.834 --> 43:27.605 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
installed outside the
Smithsonian National
Museum of African Art.

43:27.638 --> 43:32.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's the latest in a series of
public art
works on display around the
world by the artist

43:32.443 --> 43:34.278 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Yinka Shonibare.

43:34.312 --> 43:39.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YINKA SHONIBARE, Sculptor: It's
a freestanding
sculpture, but it's a very
dynamic sculpture,

43:39.317 --> 43:41.452 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and it's very colorful.

43:41.486 --> 43:48.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, also, it's deceptive,
because, from a
distance, it feels like it's
actually soft

43:48.259 --> 43:50.061 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
material.

43:50.094 --> 43:54.765 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Playful,
deceptive, full of
contradiction, the stuff of
Shonibare's works,

43:54.799 --> 44:00.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
most of all the sculptures for
which he's
best known, colonial-style
figures, some headless,

44:00.671 --> 44:05.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some with globes for heads, in
brightly colored
African-style costumes.

44:05.076 --> 44:11.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YINKA SHONIBARE: Actually, my
work is really
breaking down stereotypes,
saying, you know

44:11.849 --> 44:12.817 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
what?

44:12.850 --> 44:15.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What you see is not necessarily
what you get.

44:15.887 --> 44:22.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you might actually want to
take time to
find out more about something
before you then

44:22.860 --> 44:24.762 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
start to make assumptions about
it.

44:24.795 --> 44:27.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Shonibare himself
is a mix
of identities.

44:27.999 --> 44:34.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Born in London in 1962, he moved
to his family's
homeland in Nigeria at 3 years
old, and then

44:34.405 --> 44:36.674 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
returned to London to study fine
art.

44:36.707 --> 44:42.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At 19, he contracted a viral
infection in
his spine that left him
partially paralyzed.

44:42.880 --> 44:47.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He also began to see his way
forward as an
artist, through an
unintentionally provocative

44:47.718 --> 44:49.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
question that came from a
teacher.

44:49.554 --> 44:54.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YINKA SHONIBARE: One of my
teachers said,
why aren't you making authentic
African art?

44:54.592 --> 45:05.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I felt that, actually, what's
authentic African
art, or what's authentic
identity in a global,

45:05.503 --> 45:07.939 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
modern world?

45:07.972 --> 45:10.908 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so those questions have been
with me since.

45:10.942 --> 45:14.679 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have explored those
questions in many
ways.

45:14.712 --> 45:20.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For example,
those so-called
African fabrics he uses,
Shonibare actually

45:20.184 --> 45:25.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
found them in the Brixton area
of London,
but they were originally batik
patterns from

45:25.423 --> 45:28.693 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Indonesia brought by the Dutch
to West Africa.

45:28.726 --> 45:34.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YINKA SHONIBARE: So, the fabric
is really
an expression of the kind of
hybrid identity.

45:34.065 --> 45:39.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I'm suggesting that it's
African, and it's
also Dutch.

45:39.203 --> 45:41.272 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's also Indonesian.

45:41.305 --> 45:42.707 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And that's OK.

45:42.740 --> 45:45.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Why are so many
of them headless
or have globes as heads?

45:45.676 --> 45:50.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YINKA SHONIBARE: First of all, I
wanted to
produce figures that didn't
belong to one

45:50.848 --> 45:51.949 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
particular race.

45:51.983 --> 45:54.185 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You wanted to
take race out
of it?

45:54.218 --> 45:57.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YINKA SHONIBARE: Yes, I wanted
to take race
out of the picture.

45:57.054 --> 46:03.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A lot of the figures are of a
mixed race.

46:03.461 --> 46:06.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They are neither white nor
black.

46:06.764 --> 46:13.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that, also, I wanted
to get away
from the binary, the dividing of
people.

46:13.404 --> 46:16.540 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I felt that we're all one
humanity.

46:16.574 --> 46:24.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I wanted to find a way to
represent one
humanity, and to also take the
race equation

46:24.715 --> 46:26.517 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
out of it.

46:26.550 --> 46:30.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But while ideas
run throughout
his work, there's also that
playfulness and

46:30.221 --> 46:32.156 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a concern for beauty and color.

46:32.189 --> 46:38.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YINKA SHONIBARE: I think it's
very important
for the audience to be able to
actually engage

46:38.262 --> 46:39.463 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with the work.

46:39.497 --> 46:42.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't want people to run away
from my work,
you know?

46:42.333 --> 46:44.168 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I want people to be attracted to
the work.

46:44.201 --> 46:46.237 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I want to draw them in.

46:46.270 --> 46:50.708 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think color is one way of
doing that.

46:50.741 --> 46:57.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then you can, if you wish to
say something,
people might be more sympathetic
or be willing

46:57.515 --> 47:00.351 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to engage and listen to you.

47:00.384 --> 47:06.424 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: A recent
sculptural installation,
titled the British Library,
6,000 books with

47:06.457 --> 47:10.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the names of immigrants who've
contributed
to British society, is a more
direct kind

47:10.995 --> 47:13.130 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of commentary on contemporary
issues.

47:13.164 --> 47:19.036 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
YINKA SHONIBARE: I don't
necessarily think
that artists can single-handedly
change the

47:19.070 --> 47:20.771 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
world.

47:20.805 --> 47:23.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that if you really
wanted to do that,
I think you should go into
politics.

47:23.941 --> 47:29.914 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that, as an artist, you
have different
concerns.

47:29.947 --> 47:37.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The work can be funny, it can be
ironic, it
can be engaging, it can be dark,
it can be

47:37.388 --> 47:43.627 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
entertaining, it can provoke,
but not -- it
should never be an instruction.

47:43.661 --> 47:47.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Can I just ask
you finally
a personal question about your
disability?

47:47.932 --> 47:50.201 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It obviously changed your life.

47:50.234 --> 47:52.036 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Did it change your art?

47:52.069 --> 47:58.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YINKA SHONIBARE: It took me a
long time to
try to recover and get back to
my profession.

47:58.109 --> 48:00.344 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I have devised ways of working.

48:00.377 --> 48:08.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have a studio with a lot of
assistants,
and I design a lot of things,
and I also paint.

48:09.019 --> 48:12.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I developed a way of working
that I'm
used to.

48:12.957 --> 48:18.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You don't see an
impact on
the content or the work itself?

48:18.329 --> 48:24.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YINKA SHONIBARE: I don't see an
impact on
the content or the work itself,
but perhaps

48:24.135 --> 48:31.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my level of empathy has actually
increased
as a result of what I have
experienced personally.

48:31.275 --> 48:36.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yinka Shonibare's
