48:57.568 --> 49:05.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: And finally
tonight, another
installment in our Brief But
Spectacular series,

49:05.409 --> 49:08.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where we ask interesting people
to describe
their passions.

49:08.412 --> 49:10.881 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Tonight, pianist Jeanne Stark.

49:10.915 --> 49:16.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her career spans seven decades,
from sold-out
performances at Carnegie Hall to
venues around

49:16.187 --> 49:17.488 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Europe.

49:17.521 --> 49:20.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Stark turns 91 this month and
shares what
keeps her playing.

49:20.691 --> 49:24.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEANNE STARK, Classical Pianist:
I am born
in Belgium.

49:24.862 --> 49:28.065 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And what do you want to know
about this?

49:28.098 --> 49:30.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
QUESTION: Well, when did music
first enter
your life?

49:30.534 --> 49:34.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEANNE STARK: Music entered my
life before
I knew it.

49:34.505 --> 49:43.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My father, he walked around with
me and sang,
and then I stopped crying, and I
smiled.

49:43.447 --> 49:53.924 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He made up his mind, hmm, see,
this is a musician.

49:53.958 --> 49:58.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Queen Elizabeth in Belgium was
very fond of
music.

49:58.529 --> 50:04.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She decided that I should have a
special scholarship
because she felt that there was
a lot of potential

50:04.602 --> 50:05.903 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
there.

50:05.936 --> 50:12.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I made my debut in the Carnegie
Recital Hall
in the year 1959.

50:12.209 --> 50:14.578 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
My teacher was Edwina Bear (ph).

50:14.612 --> 50:17.248 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She never charged me for
anything.

50:17.281 --> 50:20.050 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I remember, I said: "Thank
you.

50:20.084 --> 50:23.220 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And now I got this big concert
because of
you."

50:23.254 --> 50:26.223 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And she said, "You proved me
right."

50:26.257 --> 50:40.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have been so lucky, where all
these great
artists, Geoff Leigh, who was a
friend of

50:40.771 --> 50:42.773 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Bartok, I got them all.

50:42.806 --> 50:47.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To learn from people like that,
it takes you
years to understand what they
were saying.

50:47.745 --> 50:51.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But once you get it, you get
something very
precious.

50:51.615 --> 50:53.317 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not interpret.

50:53.350 --> 50:58.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's understand how music is
made, how it's
put together.

50:58.822 --> 51:05.095 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
QUESTION: Has your understanding
of certain
pieces evolved over the years?

51:05.129 --> 51:07.097 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEANNE STARK: Oh, yes,
enormously.

51:07.131 --> 51:09.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I will tell you one example.

51:09.533 --> 51:14.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I played Mozart's sonatas,
Beethoven's sonatas,
and I was never happy with my
adagios.

51:14.204 --> 51:17.241 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I did it with the metronome.

51:17.274 --> 51:19.310 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I tried everything.

51:19.343 --> 51:21.545 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I came to the States.

51:21.578 --> 51:27.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, by accident, my friend took
me to hear
Ray Charles.

51:27.384 --> 51:31.755 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I thought, now I know an
adagio.

51:31.789 --> 51:37.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Classical music is not being
really promoted
these days.

51:37.127 --> 51:39.563 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When I was young, it was a
golden time.

51:39.596 --> 51:46.270 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There were fantastic players,
Rachmaninoff
and Prokofiev.

51:46.303 --> 51:49.940 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And, my goodness, the
inspiration was unbelievable.

51:49.974 --> 51:57.614 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I was little, I was in a
theory class
two, three times a week.

51:57.648 --> 51:59.083 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You learn to sing.

51:59.116 --> 52:00.985 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's a great thing.

52:01.018 --> 52:04.455 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If you learn to sing, you start
to hear.

52:04.488 --> 52:06.890 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I am 90 years old.

52:06.924 --> 52:09.059 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I don't know why I am here.

52:09.093 --> 52:12.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I should be dead, because most
people are.

52:13.030 --> 52:16.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My mind is, as you can see, very
sharp.

52:16.934 --> 52:21.438 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I don't understand, but I
love the day.

52:21.472 --> 52:22.706 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I love music.

52:22.740 --> 52:24.375 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How I adore music.

52:24.408 --> 52:29.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I love to hear great music,
well-played as
well.

52:29.546 --> 52:40.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My name is Jeanne Stark, and
this is my Brief
But Spectacular take on my life
in music.

